metadata.name: Laniakea #190
metadata.description:
This piece captures the mysterious beauty of the Laniakea Supercluster, the colossal cosmic structure that contains our Milky Way galaxy.

A deep black backdrop is scattered with shimmering stars, evoking a sense of endless space and awe-inspiring expanse. Winds of dark matter are captured in the mid-ground, representing the invisible force that drives the formation of the galaxies within the Supercluster.

The foreground features a small spiral galaxy, shining brightly against the backdrop of the universe, reminding us that we are an integral part of an unimaginably grand structure.

metadata.name: Modulacions (audio) #99
metadata.description:
Modulacions (Modulations): modulation with an oscillator (carrier) with an LFO (modulator). 

-The LFO is controlled by  some of fxhash characters

-Some parameters are randomly assigned to each of the possible characters of the fxhash string (0,1,2....X,Y,Z): carrier frequency, maximum and minimum frequencies of the modulator, waveforms, views etc.

-A number of fxhash characters are selected (8,16,24,32, 40 or 48), and in order they are played and displayed using the assigned values.

-Each character is encoded in binary-> the LFO frequency is controlled: 1->maximum frequency, 0->minimum frequency.

Features:
Â·dark: black (true) or white (false).
Â·carrier_wave: wave shape of carrier oscillator (sine, square, triangle or sawtooth)
Â·modulator_mult: value of LFO multiplier.
Â·modulator_sum: value added to LFO amplitude.
Â·num_fxhash_chars: number of fxhash characters used (8,16,24,32, 40 or 48)
Â·bits_display: bits string visualization (3 types)
Â·carrier_freq_range: frequency range of carrier (low, mid or high).
Â·frames_per_bit: duration of each bit in frames.(15,20,25 or 30)

-NOTE: Headphones recomended. Some extreme sounds (frequency and amplitude) can be generated.

-p5js and p5.sound

metadata.name: Formes BinÃ ries #48
metadata.description:
"Formes BinÃ ries" (Binary Shapes) is a visualization and sonication of fxhash characters in binary code.
By default the result of the process is showed. 

you can see and listen how this final result was formed in two different ways:

SIMPLE MODE: 
Click/Touch to start.

FULL MODE:
Press any key / shake your device
(requires a large use of resources, recommended for computer)

BASICS:
-A concrete number of fxhash characters (8,16,24,32,40 or 48) are converted to binary from their ASCII code.
-A geometric shape and sound wave shape are randomly assigned: Circle+Sine Wave, Square+Square wave and Triangle+Triangle wave.
-Each bit with value '1' is visually represented with an assigned form, and 0 with nothing. Bits are represented concentrically, sequentially starting the fxhash binary string with the smallest shape, and increasing in size by each bit 1. These shapes are assigned a color according to the ASCII character to which the bit belongs bit
-The same is done with the sound part, the bits with value 1 are assigned a frequency according to the ASCII character to which they belong.

By default the result of the process is showed. 

you can see and listen how this final result was formed in two different ways:

SIMPLE MODE: 
Click/Touch to start.

FULL MODE:
Press any key / shake your device
(requires a large use of resources, recommended for computer)

Features: 

-num_chars: number of fxhash characters used (8,16,24,32,40 or 48).

-dark: black(true) or white (false) background.

-color: group of colors that are assigned to each ASCII character.

-one_thikness: all shapes has the same thikness (true) or not (false).

-shape: shape (+wave form of the sound) randomly assigned: circle, square or triangle.

-blur: value of blur.

-deviation: the shapes has a desviation on its position.

-freq_range: ran
NOTE: after a few days if 50% of mints have not been exceeded, the number of iterations will be halved.

metadata.name: Glass Ceiling v1.0 #46
metadata.description:
Toying with ideas combining form and movement, perhaps the last of my works containing only spherical shapes for a while. I will be visiting other parts of my mind for inspiration after this piece.

Sharing royalties with THREE.js (thanks for the great library) and Girls Who Code (we need more)!

Extremely rare to get 8 glass spheres... By the randomness imposed, 30% will have one sphere, 30% two, 20% three, 10% four, 5% five, 3.5% six, 1% seven and 0.5% eight. Happy hunting!

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle
Right click and drag to change the view center
Mouse wheel to change the distance to the view center

With the keyboard:

Keys "," and "." (i.e. "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed.

metadata.name: Specter of Fears #246
metadata.description:
In the dreamlike landscape of our minds, the specter of fears is like a wraith, ever-present and ethereal. It whispers in our ear, reminding us of all the things we dare not face. It is a shadow that falls across our hearts, casting a pall of doubt and uncertainty. But even as it haunts us, we must remember that it is a part of us. We must learn to accept its presence, and to use it to our advantage. For fear is not always a curse, it is a guide that shows us where we must grow stronger. It is a companion that walks with us through the dark night, illuminating the path ahead. By embracing our fears, we find the courage to face them, and to overcome them. We find the strength to live fully, to love fiercely, and to pursue our dreams with abandon.

Controls :

metadata.name: Reading a book #721
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: Floating Point  #106
metadata.description:
'Floating Point' by pixelwank 

Inspired by pastel smudging and the aerial photography of Rich Caldwell, Floating Point has impressions of a landscape and other structures. 

Homage to floating point numbers and how just one decimal difference can change it all. 

Floating Point is also the fictional name of the place where this work takes me, where does it take you?

In live mode, click the image or press 's' or 'S' to save 3000x4000 png 

Thanks for collecting 
Shoutout Circolors for the support & frenship <3
